25 δ 0. Malitiosam] Dionysius (111. 33) calls it ὕλη κακοῦργος. Both epithets mean ‘ crafty,’ ‘ cunning,' so Silva M. may be translated ‘ Wily Wood.' Did the battle name the wood, or the wood the battle? We do not know. If the former, then perhaps a successful stratagem (as in c. 14) was executed by the Romans: if the latter, we must trace the title back to a primitive belief in the deceitful or destructive powers of wood-spirits. It is worth noticing in this connection that Dionysius (v. 16) says that the Romans attributed to Faunus the same power of causing sudden panic which the Greeks ascribed to Pan.
